{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528046"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:37:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:37:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14259"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14259"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.32,0.34,0.09,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6954"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53882"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6954"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14259"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39344"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"92"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"5351"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12084"},{"type":"tags","id":"12765"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16206"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32911"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43934"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45026"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53882"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old Aboriginal man presents to the General Practice clinic concerned about hepatitis B. He was surprised to learn that his friend was recently diagnosed with the infection, and he wants to know if he should also be tested. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He lives with his mother and three siblings. There is no family history of liver disease. He smokes cannabis weekly but does not smoke cigarettes or drink alcohol, and has never injected drugs. He is sexually active with a single female partner and does not use protection, and believes she has previously been checked for sexually transmitted infections. He recently returned from a four-week holiday in Thailand. He works in education. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is an indication for hepatitis B testing in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Recreational drug use","History of unprotected sexual intercourse","Being Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander","Contact with a person with known hepatitis B","Travel to endemic region"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the most appropriate indication for hepatitis B testing is the patient\u0027s \u003Cstrong\u003EAboriginal status\u003C/strong\u003E. Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people are considered a priority population for hepatitis B testing due to higher prevalence rates compared to the non-Indigenous Australian population and higher risk of complications. Ideally, all Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders should have their hepatitis B status checked and documented, and vaccination offered if they are found to be susceptible. Other priority populations for hepatitis B testing include being born in a country with high hepatitis B prevalence, pregnancy, healthcare workers, and certain medical conditions or treatments that increase the risk of hepatitis B reactivation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecreational drug use\u003C/strong\u003E, specifically cannabis smoking, is not a direct risk factor for hepatitis B transmission, unlike intravenous drug use. While substance use can be associated with higher-risk behaviours, cannabis use alone does not necessitate hepatitis B testing. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHistory of unprotected sexual intercourse\u003C/strong\u003E can be a risk factor for hepatitis B, especially if with multiple partners or in areas of high prevalence. Having multiple sexual partners may be an indication for testing, but is not necessarily indicated in this case based on this patient\u0027s sexual history alone. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContact with a person with known hepatitis B\u003C/strong\u003E can be an indication for testing, but in this case, the patient only mentions a friend being diagnosed, not a close contact. Hepatitis B testing is indicated for individuals with family, sexual or household contacts with known or suspected hepatitis B. It is not casually transmitted through social contact, as it requires direct contact with infected blood or other body fluids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETravel to endemic region\u003C/strong\u003E is not in itself a risk factor for hepatitis B unless engaging in activities which may lead to transmission. Birth in an intermediate or high prevalence country, on the other hand, is a strong indication for hepatitis B testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that hepatitis B testing may be a sensitive subject which can trigger stigma and shame, and should be discussed and informed consent gained in a culturally appropriate and safe way. Healthcare providers should be mindful about who is present and to pay attention to language and communication. There are hepatitis B resources available which have been specifically designed for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people which can be offered.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders are a priority population for hepatitis B testing, and should be offered testing and vaccination if found to be susceptible"],"references":["Lubel, J.S., Strasser, S.I., Thompson, A.J., Cowie, B.C., MacLachlan, J., Allard, N.L., Holmes, J., Kemp, W.W., Majumdar, A., Iser, D., Howell, J. and Matthews, G.V. (2022), Australian consensus recommendations for the management of hepatitis B. Med J Aust, 216: 478-486. https://doi.org/10.5694/mja2.51430","ASHM. Indications for hepatitis B testing. 2020. Available at: https://testingportal.ashm.org.au/national-hbv-testing-policy/indications-for-hbv-testing/","Hepatitis B toolkit: caring for Aboriginal Victorians. Available at: https://ashm.org.au/hepatitis-b-toolkit/caring-for-aboriginal-victorians/","Menzies School of Health Research. Hep B Story App. 2014. Available at: https://www.menzies.edu.au/page/Resources/Hep_B_Story/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39344"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14259"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39344"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-27T14:42:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-27T14:42:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6954"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53882"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.